title: For Sale/Trade:  8mm Mauser VZ 24 Czech,German,Chinese
postcontent: This rifle is more classified as an Antique. The Rifle is not in the best condition. It will fire I have put probably about 20 rounds throught it. but the problems are that after you fire the rifle the bolt locks up and you have working harder than most rifles to eject the empty cartriges but I have had mo misfires with the rifle. also the rifling is also very worn out on this rifle. But this Rifle has Great historical value. The VZ 24 was produced from 1924 to 1942 by Czechoslovakia and was based off the Famous Gewehr 98. After the German Annexation of Czechoslovakia in 1939 the Germans obtained all of the rifle in the Arsenals and sold them to ally and non ally countries. This one was sold to the Republic of China (1912-1949) and was most likely used to fight of the Japanese that invaded in 1937. Also this Rifle has no importation marks so it would have most likely been captured by Communist Chinese forces and ended up in America most likely from an American GI Bringing it home from the Korean War. postcontent: Selling a 1943 dated M44 Mosin Nagant. These are the rare "trials rifles". Also called "prototypes" in the collector community. The design was a success so the Red Army adopted it as the rifle model 44 in 1944. This is one is in good shape and is a good shooter. title: For Sale:  Skorpion vs.61 Czech SOLD
postcontent: SOLDOriginal CZ Scorpion model vs 61 was developed by Czechoslovakia in the late 1950's as an easily concealed submachine gun.  Chambered for the 9x18 Makarov caliber, this is a semi-auto copy.  New, unfired.  Similar design to the MP5K, but much smaller, lighter, easier to handle, and about a third the price.  Check YouTube for bump fire videos, apparently the design makes it obtainable without special stock.  It utilizes the telescoping bolt like the Uzi.  Overall length of 10.75 inches, barrel length of 4.53 inches, weight of 2.54 pounds without magazine and 3.15 pounds with fully loaded mag.  The frame is drilled and tapped for attaching the folding stock mounting plate.Included is the OEM hard case, 2 - 20 rd magazines, mag pouch, holster that can be worn either as a hip or thigh holster, bore brush, users manual, Czech Small Arms decal, and 5 years manufacturer's warranty.Civilian (Semi-auto) models of Skorpion (European) Scorpion (USA) have been produced by Czech-USA in three calibers: 7.65 Br, 9x17, and 9x18 Makarov.  Of those three calibers, the 9x18 has the most reasonably priced ammo.  Everyone would like to have the Skorpion in 9x19 or 9mm Luger.  Efforts were made by the Czechs to manufacture a 9x19 version, but the size had to be greatly increased to handle the higher pressure of the round.  There is a U.S. company "Armitage" that produced a 9x19 pistol they called a "Scorpion".  Only 602 were produced, there is usually a couple listed on line.  Reviews I have seen on that pistol, said you were lucky to empty a mag without a stoppage.This model is "out of stock" at CzechPoint.  Since the pistol is manufactured using some surplus parts, there will come a time that new ones will no longer be available.  Get yours while you can.  Through a SNAFU, I ended up with two, that is the only reason this one is for sale. $625 FTF in NW Columbus.  OBROShipped to FFL at buyer's expense.Trade:  Military high power9mm or .45 1911
